				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">That was unique - hit post reply, and it refreshs to the thread and I'm not the last post <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="Razz" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
I would agree with the above on Microsoft trackballs - the ones I've used tend to have strange extra buttons with frustrating default bindings.
<br />

<br />
I'm not so sure on the driver issue - I avoided installing LogiTech drivers until this year (been using the (same) mice for 7 years now), and I've been very pleased with how the new drivers perform.  On Windows98, or at least my copy, Windows detected and configured for this style of trackball appropriately and I never felt the need to mess with it.  Win2k did not detect it well, and labelled it a default 2 button mouse - overriding that to the proper windows driver actually <span style="font-style: italic">degraded</span> performance.  When I finally installed Logitech mouseware, all the precision pointing and jerky movement problems went away - I hadn't even realized that they were an issue until I had the problem-free version for comparison.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
